article.description:
Jessica Moore had 24 points 
and nine rebounds as No. 1 Connecticut posted a 78-58, Big East
Conference victory over West Virginia to extend its NCAA
Division I record winning streak to 68 games.
article.headline: Huskies win 10th straight Big East regular-season title
article.linkText: UConn clinches another perfect regular season
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut cruised past West Virginia Tuesday night, then threw a party at center court.

<photo1>

Complete with trophy, caps and T-shirts, there was plenty to celebrate.

The Huskies (29-0, 16-0 Big East) had just defeated West Virginia 78-58, extending the nation's longest winning streak to 68 games. They also finished back-to-back unbeaten regular seasons.

And they did it with just one returning starter from last season's NCAA title team, beating Tennessee and Duke along the way.

"To win them all I think it's been pretty remarkable for this group,'' coach Geno Auriemma said.

The Huskies wrapped up their 10th straight Big East regular-season conference championship Saturday with a 70-52 win over Providence. They were presented with the trophy after Tuesday's game to a standing ovation from the 16,000 at the Hartford Civic Center.

The Huskies are 20 wins away from tying the NCAA record of 88 straight set by UCLA's men from 1971-74.

UConn is the second Division I women's team to string together consecutive undefeated regular seasons. Vermont did it from 1991-93 with records of 29-0 and 28-0.

"I'm really proud of these kids,'' Auriemma said. "I challenged them from the end of last season to preseason, every single day, to prove to me that they were as good as they thought they were. I was kind of excited to play this game tonight.''

   Jessica Moore led UConn with a career-high 24 points and grabbed
nine rebounds. She was out to make up for her lackluster appearance
in Saturday's win at Providence, in which she played just 16
minutes.

"That was my goal, to come in here and play like I was mad at the world,'' Moore said.

Diana Taurasi, the only returning starter from the 2001-02
national championship team, finished with 20 points for UConn. She
and Ashley Battle each had eight rebounds.

Kate Bulger led the Mountaineers (15-12, 4-12) with 25 points
and Michelle Carter added 12. Teammate Eartha White had a team-high
10 rebounds.

The Huskies wasted little time securing win No. 68 over the Big
East team with the longest losing drought against them. The
Mountaineers have not beaten UConn in 20 years.

Taurasi's layup with 16:21 left in the first half kicked off a
22-0 run, and the Mountaineers never recovered. UConn did most of
its damage in transition and converted easy buckets down low.

Moore had 16 of her points in the first half, nearly all in the
post, as UConn took a 42-23 lead at the break. The southpaw center
anchored a solid inside game as the Huskies outrebounded the
Mountaineers 51-29 and outscored them 46-20 in the paint.

"She destroyed us,'' West Virginia coach Mike Carey said.
"She's active and she's aggressive and she's left-handed. You
don't see a lot of players, especially at the post, who are left-handed.''

Taurasi said the unbeaten season exceeded the expectations of
many, including her coach.

"We worked hard throughout the season,'' Taurasi said. "I think every month we got a little bit better on everything we wanted to improve on. It's definitely a good springboard for the Big East tournament and hopefully deep into March.''
